poemContent: Oben den Hügel, liegt es den alten Bull & BushA Bush and a Bull, can’t see them around,Just in gothic writing, on the north facing pub.So where are they hidden -      The Bush and the Bull? The toilets, the kitchen, or under the Müll? The white building? UnlikelyFor beasts that mighty. But maybe I’m wrong.  The bull was me, for it climbed the bush, In an electrical substation; eternal damnation, Danger of death! 415 volts. But you won’t die; it's between screws and bolts.  For it seems like a tube stationRather than a substation,Clickety clack, knew t’was that! Artificial crescendo; where are they off to? Air turbulence shows, it blows to the north. This dust has a familiar smell; The smell of decay, the stench of rocks.  It’s appeared on the headlines countless times For its particulates are known for scarring lungs.  Yet who can resist this landmark of London? Turning right towards the circular shaft, Hier liegt ein Sign der sagt: Depth of shaft: 38 metres My wheel touches the first stair of the shaft. Spiralling down in a spiral of decay, Like Mr Statin’s might; I picture its plight. Slamming the breaks, bike  Crashed on the landing, Just like the empire of OzyAndy.  Rushing down to platform level, A train whizzed south from north; a furious rebel.Its destination read ‘‘express to history’’ of the Hill’s largest port.   Once a trading spot; largest depot, At the world’s poshest school, now among the level sands.  Like a dead old bull decaying in a bush, OzyAndy’s statue crumbles, On what once was a platform.  Reduced to rubbles.
